<div2>
<opener>
                                                                            <dateline>February 27, 1926.</dateline>

<address>
<addrLine>Mr. John G. Neihardt,</addrLine>
<addrLine>Branson, Mo.</addrLine>
</address>

<salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
</opener>
<p>In one of your recent letters, you suggested that we ought to get up a little booklet on THE SONG OF THE INDIAN WARS, and you offered to prepare the material. I would be very glad if you would do this, and will see that prompt use is made of it in our spring campaign on your work.</p>
<closer>
<salute>Sincerely yours,</salute>

<signed>H.S. Latham<lb/>
                  K</signed>

<note>HSL.K</note>
</closer>
</div2>

                            <div2>
<opener>
<salute>Dearest Comrade:</salute>
</opener>
<p>I'll furnish the press clippings for this booklet. Would you have time to do a brief <del/>article (say 300 words) to be used in the booklet, and covering the significance of the three volumes of the cycle published, with especial emphasis on the <hi rend="underline">Wars</hi>? If so, I should have the stuff very soon.</p>

<p>I'm jumping sidewise with my page for the Journal-Post, but am pushing <hi rend="underline">Messiah</hi> too, - faster than usual. Might mention Collected Poems to be published in the Fall &amp; comment on scope &amp; volume thereof.</p>
<closer>
<salute>Love,</salute> <signed>Jno</signed>
</closer>
</div2>       

<note type="authorial">I'll answer your good letter soon. So glad Mary is Mary House again.</note>       
     
<note type="authorial"><hi rend="underline">Latest Idea:</hi> I think, if you can write the brief article, it should be sent direct to H.S. Latham by you. I'll send the other stuff from here.</note>  
<note type="authorial">You would probably remark <unclear>in passing</unclear> that <hi rend="underline">Friends</hi> + Glass are already "classics" spreading widely in the schools</note>                     
                     </div1>
